JOHANNESBURG &#8211; South Africa&#8217;s rand held on to a three-week high against the dollar early on Tuesday, buoyed by increased risk appetite after the market&#8217;s preferred candidate won the first round of the French presidential election.At 0645 GMT, the rand traded at 12.9825 per dollar, from its New York close of 13.0175/dollar on Monday.The rand has been trading at three-week highs since Monday, when it reached 12.8800/dollar, as emerging-market assets rose after Emmanuel Macron, a pro-European Union and former economy minister of France, qualified for the May 7 runoff against far-right leader Marine Le Pen.Stocks were set to open flat at 0700 GMT, with the JSE securities exchange&#8217;s Top-40 futures index largely unchanged.In fixed income, the yield for the benchmark government bond due in 2026 fell 1 basis point to 8.625%. 